When money is divided in ratio of $\frac{1}{2}$ : $\frac{1}{3}$ : $\frac{1}{4}$
Ratio of shares = $\frac{1}{2}$ : $\frac{1}{3}$ : $\frac{1}{4}$ = 6 : 4 : 3.
P's share = ₹ $\left(117\times\frac{6}{13}\right)$ = ₹ 54;
Q's share = ₹ $\left(117\times\frac{4}{13}\right)$ = ₹ 36;
R's share = ₹ $\left(117\times\frac{3}{13}\right)$ = ₹ 27.
When money is divided in ratio of 2 : 3 : 4
P's share = ₹ $\left(117\times\frac{2}{9}\right)$ = ₹ 26;
Q's share = ₹ $\left(117\times\frac{3}{9}\right)$ = ₹ 39;
R's share = ₹ $\left(117\times\frac{4}{9}\right)$ = ₹ 52.
Clearly, both Q and R gained in the transaction.

Let the containers A, B and C contain $5x, 4x$ and $5x$ litres of mixtures respectively.
Milk in A $= \left(5x\times\frac{1}{6}\right)$ litres $= \frac{5}{6}x$ litres;
Water in A $= \left(5x - \frac{5}{6}x\right)$ litres $= \frac{25}{6}x$ litres.
Milk in B $= \left(4x\times\frac{3}{8}\right)$ litres $= \frac{3}{2}x$ litres;
Water in B $= \left(4x - \frac{3}{2}x\right)$ litres $= \frac{5}{2}x$ litres.
Milk in C $= \left(5x\times\frac{5}{12}\right)$ litres $= \frac{25}{12}x$ litres;
Water in C $= \left(5x - \frac{25}{12}x\right)$ litres $= \frac{35}{12}x$ litres.
Total milk in final mixture $= \left(\frac{5}{6} + \frac{3}{2} + \frac{25}{12}\right)x$ litres $= \frac{53}{12}x$ litres.
Total water in final mixture $= \left(\frac{25}{6} + \frac{5}{2} + \frac{35}{12}\right)x$ litres $= \frac{115}{12}x$ litres.
Required ratio of milk and water $= \frac{53}{12} : \frac{115}{12} = 53 : 115$.

Milk in 1st glass $= \frac{1}{2}$ unit; Milk in second glass $= \frac{2}{3}$ unit;
Milk in 3rd glass $= \frac{3}{4}$ unit;
Water in 1st glass $= \frac{1}{2}$ unit;
Water in second glass $= \frac{1}{3}$ unit;
Water in 3rd glass $= \frac{1}{4}$ unit.
Required ratio $= \frac{\frac{1}{2} + \frac{2}{3} + \frac{3}{4}}{\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{4}} = \frac{\frac{6+8+9}{12}}{\frac{6+4+3}{12}} = \frac{23}{13}$.
